  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why does the wireless capability on my smartphone keep turning off?",
  "response": "There are several potential reasons why the wireless capability (Wi-Fi) on your smartphone keeps turning off. Here are some common causes and troubleshooting steps to help you resolve the issue:\n\n### 1. **Battery Saver Mode or Power Saving Settings**\n   - Many smartphones automatically turn off Wi-Fi when the battery is low or when battery saver mode is enabled to conserve power.\n   - **Solution**: Check your battery settings and disable battery saver mode or adjust power-saving settings to ensure Wi-Fi remains active.\n\n### 2. **Wi-Fi Sleep Settings**\n   - Some phones have a feature that turns off Wi-Fi when the device is idle or sleeping to save battery.\n   - **Solution**: Go to your Wi-Fi settings and adjust the \"Keep Wi-Fi on during sleep\" option (usually found in Advanced Wi-Fi settings) to ensure Wi-Fi stays on.\n\n### 3. **Network Reset or Software Glitch**\n   - A software glitch or misconfiguration could cause the Wi-Fi to turn off unexpectedly.\n   - **Solution**: Reset your network settings (this will erase saved Wi-Fi networks and Bluetooth connections, so you\u2019ll need to reconnect afterward). Go to **Settings > System > Reset > Reset Network Settings**.\n\n### 4. **Bad Wi-Fi Signal or Connectivity Issues**\n   - If the Wi-Fi signal is weak or unstable, your phone may automatically switch to mobile data or turn Wi-Fi off.\n   - **Solution**: Move closer to the router or test with a different Wi-Fi network to see if the issue persists.\n\n### 5. **Software Update or Bug**\n   - A recent software update may have introduced a bug affecting Wi-Fi functionality.\n   - **Solution**: Check for system updates in **Settings > Software Update** and install any available updates. If the issue started after an update, consider reporting it to the manufacturer.\n\n### 6. **App Interference**\n   - A third-party app with permissions to control Wi-Fi or battery settings could be causing the issue.\n   - **Solution**: Uninstall recently installed apps or check for apps with Wi-Fi control permissions in settings.\n\n### 7. **Hardware Issue**\n   - If none of the above solutions work, there may be a hardware issue with your phone\u2019s Wi-Fi module.\n   - **Solution**: Contact the manufacturer or a certified repair center for diagnostics and repair.\n\n### 8. **Automated Settings or Routines**\n   - Some smartphones have automation features (e.g., Bixby Routines on Samsung or Automation on iPhone Shortcuts) that may turn off Wi-Fi based on specific triggers.\n   - **Solution**: Check for any automated routines or settings that might be disabling Wi-Fi.\n\nIf the issue persists after trying these steps, it may be worth backing up your data and performing a factory reset as a last resort, or seeking professional assistance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
